09:51.120 --> 10:00.100
For many years, astronomers learned about the universe by looking at it in the
narrow part of the electromagnetic spectrum called visible light. Later they

10:00.100 --> 10:09.900
discovered that stars send out kinds of energy that we cannot see, such as
infrared and ultraviolet radiation, radio waves, x-rays, and gamma rays. Each

10:09.900 --> 10:17.700
part of the spectrum has its own contributions to make to our understanding of
the universe. The Gamma Ray Observatory, scheduled to be launched by the Space

10:17.700 --> 10:27.920
Shuttle in 1988, will be a powerful tool for understanding some of the most
fascinating objects in space. Pulsars, quasars, active galaxies, and black

10:27.920 --> 10:37.680
holes. Dr. Donald Kniffen is Project Scientist for the Gamma Ray Observatory at
NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center. Whenever one of these violent events takes

10:37.680 --> 10:51.280
place in the universe, a supernova explosion or a black hole or a pulsar, lots
of very, very energetic processes take place. And because gamma rays are such

10:51.280 --> 11:02.580
high energy, that means in these processes, in these interactions which occur,
then a lot of energy is available to go into things like gamma rays. Now, the

11:02.580 --> 11:13.780
way that we learn about any object, viewing it through astronomy, You have to
deduce what's going on in the vicinity of the place where the gamma rays are

11:13.780 --> 11:24.560
being produced by the things that you can see. Gamma rays, like any other
photon, travel directly from the source to us so we can make a good guess as to

11:24.560 --> 11:34.020
what object they're coming from. But what we want to learn about by observing
the gamma rays is what mechanism is occurring. This then tells us about the

11:34.020 --> 11:43.880
physics that's going on in the source and hence what sort of types of violent
reactions are taking place. And from this then we can learn about things like

11:43.880 --> 11:56.480
the evolution of our universe. We can learn about the actual details of the
supernova process where very heavy elements are believed to be formed. Dr. David

11:56.480 --> 12:03.740
Thompson, also from the Goddard Space Flight Center, explain some of the
contributions the Gamma Ray Observatory can make. The observatory will help us

12:03.740 --> 12:16.360
understand pulsars. Pulsars were first discovered by radio astronomers, and it
is now thought that a pulsar is a rapidly rotating remnant of a star that once

12:16.360 --> 12:27.820
lived. When that star died in a supernova explosion, it left behind a tiny core
of material, extremely dense material. If you had a sugar cube made out of

12:27.820 --> 12:37.800
neutron star material, it would weigh about 300 million tons on the surface of
the Earth, a sugar cube. So this is what a neutron star is like. These neutron

12:37.800 --> 12:49.780
stars are spinning. And as they spin, they put out pulses of radio emission. And
some of these are now known to put out pulses of gamma ray emission. Those that

12:49.780 --> 13:02.820
we have studied indicate that even though there are lots more radio waves seen
from these, most of the energy that we see coming out of a pulsar is actually in

13:02.820 --> 13:14.260
the form of gamma rays. And that means that by studying the gamma rays, we learn
something about what it's like around a neutron star, a place that's so exotic

13:14.260 --> 13:22.960
and foreign that we can't even picture it on Earth. Quasars also emit tremendous
amounts of energy in the form of gamma rays. Quasars have always been considered

13:22.960 --> 13:31.180
exotic because they appear to be moving away from us at a large fraction of the
speed of light, which may indicate that they are somewhere and they are very

13:31.180 --> 13:39.120
distant parts of the universe. And yet the fact that we can see them indicates
that they are radiating tremendous amounts of energy and may indeed be powered

13:39.120 --> 13:48.280
by black holes. If you want to see what's going on near a black hole, you have
to get out something that involves a large amount of energy, and that's a gamma

13:48.280 --> 13:48.540
ray.

13:51.440 --> 14:00.060
