14:38.080 --> 14:47.620
Recent events, such as the 1982 and 83 disastrous El Nino current, which caused
billions of dollars in damage and considerable loss of life, have demonstrated

14:47.620 --> 14:55.780
the need to better understand the workings of the ocean and its effects on our
climate. In the past, satellites have been the key to global measurements of the

14:55.780 --> 15:05.840
ocean. One of the instruments on NASA's 1979 CSAT satellite made as many
individual measurements of wind speed and direction as were collected during the

15:05.840 --> 15:15.980
previous century of shipboard observations. NASA has invited an oceanographer to
fly on the next space shuttle mission. Australian-born Paul Scully Power will be

15:15.980 --> 15:26.520
performing three major functions during this flight. The first is to test the
hypothesis, if you will, that a trained oceanographer up there can see more than

15:26.520 --> 15:38.740
an astronaut who's highly trained but not in that particular field. And the
second thing is going to be that in recent flights, the astronauts have made

15:38.740 --> 15:46.520
some significant new discoveries in oceanography from their flights. For
example, they have discovered a new type of ocean eddy which has a spiral

15:46.520 --> 15:54.380
structure, most of the ocean eddies that you find in the scientific literature
all sort of, the currents are circular. In these new type of eddies were found

15:54.380 --> 16:02.560
the currents are in fact spiral. And so there's a recent discovery made by the
astronaut crews. And so my second objective is to go look at these new

16:02.560 --> 16:10.800
discoveries that they've seen and try and interpret that. And the third major
objective is that on this particular flight, it's an Earth Sciences Mission, and

16:10.800 --> 16:18.260
specifically they're going to have a synthetic aperture radar looking at the
solid Earth and on the oceans. And so I will probably be taking photographs

16:19.320 --> 16:29.960
simultaneously with the radar of the ocean sites that the radar is capturing on
the radar imaging system. I will be in fact capturing those same sites in colour

16:29.960 --> 16:38.240
photography. Both world weather and long term climate changes are strongly
linked to ocean behaviour. The weather we've had in the last 18 months has been

16:38.240 --> 16:51.500
tied now directly to the North Pacific in terms of anomalous temperature, so
it's very obvious and there's a time lag too. The weather patterns that we've

16:51.500 --> 16:59.740
seen have been triggered by temperature anomalies in the ocean which occurred
six months previously to that. so there's a time lag. So obviously, if you're

16:59.740 --> 17:08.000
going to be able to do long-term weather prediction you've got to understand the
ocean. And that really makes a lot of sense, and I think everyone's in general

17:08.000 --> 17:15.780
agreement with that because if you think of the ocean as a sort of big heat
reservoir, it's like a big heat engine that drives the atmosphere. So what

17:15.780 --> 17:23.800
happens in the atmosphere is in fact driven by the ocean, and not the other way
around. Okay, so therefore oceanography is important. Then in the last two or

17:23.800 --> 17:30.920
three years there's been some theoretical work in oceanography that says if
you're ever going to understand the ocean dynamics you have to focus on what is

17:30.920 --> 17:42.700
called the Mese scale, what that translates to is mid scale and that really is
you know events that have size, if you will, of tens to hundreds of miles, okay.

17:43.580 --> 17:50.820
For example ocean eddies, and the more we learn about oceanography the more
we're finding that there's more and more eddies in the ocean. They have

17:50.820 --> 18:02.140
diameters of anywhere say between 70 and 150 miles. So it's right in that mid
scale. Now it turns out that from low earth orbit on the shuttle the natural

18:02.140 --> 18:12.840
field of view of the human eye or camera system is that scale. So obviously the
correct vantage point to see the whole pattern at that scale is from low earth

18:12.840 --> 18:21.840
orbit. And so that's one of the rationales as to why I'm due to fly on the
shuttle to take advantage of that particular viewing mode. And so you see the

18:21.840 --> 18:31.200
connectivity then from what I'm seeing to the mid-sized patterns in the ocean
which drives the total ocean dynamics, which drives the atmosphere. And so we

18:31.200 --> 18:34.280
can predict the long-term weather prediction. So it really is all tied together.

